records.dc:title: Estate map of Logan Estate at Brookfield, Brisbane, 1922
records.dc:creator: Unidentified
records.dc:subject: maps plans land sales land auctions Brisbane - Suburbs - Brookfield, 1922 Brookfield (Brisbane, Qld.)
records.dc:description: This real estate map (no. 910) shows Upper Brookfield and Pullenvale. (Description supplied with photograph) Auctioneers: Barnes & Co. Ltd., Roma St., Brisbane. Surveyors: R.A. Hamilton & James, 171 Queen Street. Brookfield, regarded as one of Brisbane's later developing suburbs, actually was one of the earliest areas settled. The fertile country in the district was farmed as early as 1850 with dairying and small crops being the main occupation. By the early 1870s population growth warranted the establishment of the first primary school in the area. Timber getting was also an early industry and there are the remains of a number of old gold mines in the district. Brookfield remained a quiet farming community until recent years when it became one of Brisbane's 'Green Belt' suburbs with larger housing blocks preserving the pleasant bush setting. Brookfield was named by either Mrs L. Logan, an early resident, because of the abundance of meadows, creeks and gullies, or by Mrs Lucinda Brimblecombe in 1868 at a residents' meeting to give the district a name. Mrs Brimblecombe is reported to have suggested that since the area had so many flowing brooks the district should be called Brookfield. (Information taken from: Brisbane Suburbs and Localities: Information from the Queensland Place Names Board)

records.dc:title: Witton Township real estate map, Indooroopilly, Brisbane, ca. 1880s
records.dc:creator: Unidentified
records.dc:subject: maps land auctions land sales plans suburbs Brisbane - Suburbs - Indooroopilly, ca. 1880s Indooroopilly (Brisbane, Qld.)
records.dc:description: The property of Andrew Bogle Esq. To be sold by John w. Todd, Auctioneer. The land in this direction having an area of over 70 acres with extensive river frontages and beautiful sites, will be sold in lots to suit purchasers requiring from 5 to 30 acres. (information on map) Map includes Ormond Terrace, Witton Road, Spring Street, Boundary Road, Bridge Street, Maud Street, Market Street, Rennies Road and shows the location of Witton Manor. Indooroopilly is a leafy riverside suburb in Brisbane's west and derives its name from either the Aboriginal term for running water or gully of leeches. The suburb was first settled in 1860 when Mr H C Rawnsley purchased land south of Witton Creek and in 1861 built the first house in the area, named Witton Manor, on the site of the present Nudgee Junior College. Development was slow until 1875 when a rail service was provided from Brisbane, after which houses and firms soon sprang up. In 1876 the first railway bridge was built. This was swept away in the disastrous 1893 flood, but was rebuilt. The Walter Taylor Bridge (commonly known as the Indooroopilly Toll Bridge) was built in 1936 and linked Indooroopilly to Chelmer. (Information taken from: Queensland Place Names Board: Brisbane Suburbs and Localities)

records.dc:title: Toohey's City View Estate Map, Greenslopes, Brisbane, Queensland, 1914
records.dc:creator: Unidentified
records.dc:subject: building blocks maps land auctions Brisbane- Suburbs- Greenslopes, 1914 Logan Road (Greenslopes, Qld.)
records.dc:description: Advertisement for a real estate land sale to be conducted by G. H. Blocksidge & Ferguson, auctioneers, on the site of Toohey's Estate. At one stage the Greenslopes of today, and the surrounding area, was dense forest, criss-crossed by ridges and gullies. It attracted many timber-fellers who took materials for building and fencing from the district. The district began its development because a number of German migrants settled on the banks of the Logan River. They made a rough bush track from their farming lands to Brisbane and this eventually developed further into the Logan Road-Pacific Highway route of modern days. (Information taken from : Brisbane Suburbs and Localities: Information from the Queensland Place Names Board)

records.dc:description: Estate map showing allotments to be sold on 16 May 1914 by G. T. Bell and Chandler & Russell, auctioneers. The land was surveyed by Thor. H. Jensen. The plan includes a local sketch. The estate covers an area adjacent to Crown Street, Crump Street, Agnes Street and Baynes Road (later known as Swain Street). The land being advertised for sale was originally owned by Antoine Charles Crump and was the site of his slaughter yards. Antoine was born at Newton St. Cyres, Devonshire, on a farm called 'Hill Farm', 22 Nov 1843. Note the name of the subdivision. He left England for Brisbane in 1864 and in 1867 married Margaret Naughton. Mr Crump developed a chain of five ot six butcher shops across Brisbane, some of which were run by his sons. Richard Crump ran the shop at Boggo Road, Fairfield; John Frederick Roberts Crump ran the one at Kelvin Grove and Charles Crump ran the Annerley shop.

records.dc:creator: Unidentified
records.dc:subject: maps plans land sales land auctions Brisbane - Suburbs - Chermside, ca. 1888 Chermside (Brisbane, Qld.)
records.dc:description: Five Mile Town Estate, Gympie Road. Apply: A. Hamilton, Downfall Creek Post Office. The present district of Chermside was originally known as Downfall Creek. The name was changed to Chermside in 1903 in honour of Sir Herbert Charles Chermside who was the Governor of Queensland from 1901 to 1944. Although the first land sales were held in 1865 the area remained devoted to farming until the turn of the century when the first urban subdivisions were offered for sale. Two such estates were the Polsloc Estate and the Five Mile Town estate which were on either side of the present main shopping centre. (Information taken from: Brisbane Suburbs and Localities: Information from the Queensland Place Names Board, and Brisbites Suburban Sites, retrieved 29 June 2004, from: <http://www.brisbites.com/suburbView.asp?suburb=26&topic=1>)
